[[Theatre Royal, Plymouth|Theatre Royal]]|accessdate=16 November 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222002239/http://www.theatreroyal.com/content.asp?CategoryID=974|archivedate=22 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> its Drum Theatre (200 capacity),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatreroyal.com/content.asp?CategoryID=975|title=Drum Theatre|publisher=The [[Theatre Royal, Plymouth|Theatre Royal]]|accessdate=16 November 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222002244/http://www.theatreroyal.com/content.asp?CategoryID=975|archivedate=22 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and its newly built production and creative learning centre, The TR2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatreroyal.com/content.asp?CategoryID=976|title=TR2|publisher=The [[Theatre Royal, Plymouth|Theatre Royal]]|accessdate=16 November 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081025075832/http://www.theatreroyal.com/content.asp?CategoryID=976|archivedate=25 October 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Plymouth Pavilions]] has multi uses for the city staging music concerts, basketball matches and stand-up comedy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plymouthpavilions.com/content.asp?CategoryID=979|title=About Us|publisher=The [[Plymouth Pavilions]]|accessdate=16 November 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822083430/http://www.plymouthpavilions.com/content.asp?CategoryID=979|archivedate=22 August 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are also three cinemas. The [[Plymouth City Museum and Art Gallery]] is operated by Plymouth City Council allowing free admission \u2013 it has six galleries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plymouth.gov.uk/homepage/creativityandculture/museums/museumpcmag.htm|title=Plymouth City Museum and Art Gallery|publisher=Plymouth City Council|accessdate=17 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nPlymouth is the sub-regional television centre of [[BBC South West]].<ref name=\"Spotlight address footnote\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/spotlight/|title=Spotlight (address footnote)|publisher=[[BBC South West]]|accessdate=17 November 2008}}</ref> Plymouth is the regional television centre of [[BBC South West]].<ref name=\"Spotlight address footnote\"/> A team of journalists are headquartered at Plymouth for the [[ITV West Country]] regional station, after a merger with [[ITV West]] forced [[ITV Westcountry]] to close on 16 February 2009. The main local newspapers serving Plymouth are [[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Herald]] and [[Western Morning News]] with [[BBC Radio Devon]] and [[Heart West]] being the main local radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plymouth.gov.uk/homepage/business/invest/sectors/creativesector.htm|title=Creative Sector|publisher=Plymouth City Council|accessdate=17 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Plymouth Culture, an arts and cultural development agency,<ref>{{cite web|title=Plymouth Culture: Home|url=http://plymouthculture.co.uk|website=plymouthculture.co.uk|accessdate=12 February 2017}}</ref> was set up to provide strategic direction for cultural development across the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Plymouth Culture is looking for new members - could it be you?|author=Emily Smith|date=19 September 2014|url=http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/8203-plymouth-culture-looking-new-members/story-22951509-detail/story.html|newspaper=Plymouth Herald}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Theatres and cinemas ==\nThe [[Theatre Royal, Plymouth|Theatre Royal]] is a provincial producing theatre and incorporates a studio theatre (The Drum). Its production and education centre, TR2, is in an award-winning building at Cattedown.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2003/building_award.shtml TR2 is Britain's \"Building of the Year\", BBC website.] Retrieved 13 October 2007.</ref> The Barbican Theatre is in a converted Mission.[http://www.barbicantheatre.co.uk/]. The university has two well-equipped theatres within the [[Roland Levinsky Building]]. Amateurs perform at the Devonport Playhouse and the Globe Theatre (within Stonehouse barracks). The [[Plymouth Pavilions]] stages music concerts from rock and pop to ballet, as well as hosting basketball, wrestling and line dancing.\n\nThere is a small cinema at Derry's Cross. In Looe Street, Plymouth Arts Centre has a single screen cinema specialising in [[art house]] and foreign films. The Levinsky arts building at the university has a film centre and there is a [[Vue (cinema)|Vue cinema]] at the Barbican Leisure Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plymouth.gov.uk/cinemas |title=Cinemas |publisher=Plymouth City Council |accessdate=17 November 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609121113/http://www.plymouth.gov.uk/cinemas |archivedate=9 June 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n== Museums, art galleries and historic buildings ==\n[[Image:National Marine Aquarium.jpg|thumb|The [[National Marine Aquarium, Plymouth|National Marine Aquarium]] is located in Plymouth.]]\n[[Image:The Citadel, Plymouth, England.jpg|right|thumb|The [[Royal Citadel, Plymouth|Royal Citadel]] at night.]]\nThe [[Plymouth City Museum and Art Gallery]] in Drake Circus has collections of fine and decorative arts, natural history and human history.\n\nThe [[Plymouth Arts Centre]], established in 1948, is located near the Barbican, and regularly offers visiting displays of work by a wide range of local, British and international artists such as [[Beryl Cook]], [[Richard Deacon (sculptor)|Richard Deacon]], [[Andy Goldsworthy]] and [[Sir Terry Frost]]. As well as promoting visual arts, many independent [[Art film|art house]] and foreign films are shown.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.plymouth.gov.uk/artstestitem?id=111163 \n |title=Plymouth City Council \u2013 Arts \n |publisher=www.plymouth.gov.uk \n |accessdate=13 March 2008 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312174411/http://www.plymouth.gov.uk/artstestitem?id=111163 \n |archivedate=12 March 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\nA converted church on North Hill, now the Sherwell Centre and part of the university, hosts regular exhibitions, concerts, recitals, lectures and other public events. There are smaller and privately owned retail galleries in [[Barbican, Plymouth|the Barbican]].\n\nAlso in Plymouth are the [[Plymouth and West Devon Record Office]], [[Smeaton's Tower]], the Elizabethan House, and Merchants House in The Barbican. Plymouth is home to the [[National Marine Aquarium, Plymouth, England|National Marine Aquarium]]. The [[Plymouth Synagogue]], in Catherine Street, was built in 1762.\n\n[[Plymouth Naval Base Museum]] is a [[maritime museum]] under development at [[HMNB Devonport]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.plymouthnavalmuseum.com/ |title=Plymouth Naval Base Museum website |access-date=4 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310190249/http://www.plymouthnavalmuseum.com/ |archive-date=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Nightlife ==\n[[Union Street, Plymouth|Union Street]] has been the centre of Plymouth's nightlife for over a century.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} Previously lined with [[music hall]]s and cinemas, the street is now run down<ref name=\"usbbc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/content/articles/2006/07/12/union_street_community_feature.shtml |title=BBC \u2013 Devon \u2013 Community Life \u2013 Union Street: night and day |publisher=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=8 March 2008}}</ref> but is still home to a number of bars, clubs and casinos. Although most clubs play commercial dance and [[R&B]], there are some which play less popular genres.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} Other clubs and bars are at the Barbican Leisure Park and on Lockyer Street. There are a number of bars with live music. [[Mutley Plain]] and North Hill have many student bars.\n[[File:Oral Histories - The Lockyer Tavern by Plymouth LGBT Archive.webm|thumb|The Lockyer Tavern; oral history]]\n[[Image:Plymouth Cliff Road.jpg|thumb|800px|centre|Looking towards the sea, from Cliff Road near the Hoe]]\n\n== Media ==\nPlymouth is a sub-regional [[BBC Television Centre|television centre]] of [[BBC South West]]. A team of journalists are headquartered at Plymouth for the [[ITV West Country]] regional station, after a merger with [[ITV West]] forced [[ITV Westcountry]] to close on 16 February 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/end-era/article-695073-detail/article.html|title=The end of an era: Last night for Westcountry TV|date=13 February 2009|publisher=[[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Herald]]|accessdate=4 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214201357/http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/end-era/article-695073-detail/article.html|archive-date=14 February 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe regional stations include [[BBC Radio Devon]], [[BBC Radio Cornwall]], [[Heart West]] and [[Pirate FM]].\n\nThe main regional newspaper is the [[Western Morning News]], whose local publishing and print centre at Derriford were designed by architect [[Nicholas Grimshaw]]. The local city paper, from the same publisher, [[Northcliffe Media]] group, at the same print centre, is the [[The Herald (Plymouth Evening Herald)|Plymouth ''Herald'']].\n\n[[Hospital Radio Plymouth]] is a station dedicated to the city's patients, broadcasting to Derriford Hospital, The Royal Eye Infirmary and on 87.7fm.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Sport in Plymouth]]\n* [[Culture of Devon]]\n* [[Culture of the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Media in Cornwall]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Culture Of Plymouth}}\n[[Category:Plymouth, Devon]]\n[[Category:Culture by city in England|Plymouth]]\n", "name_user": "Johnsoniensis", "label": "safe", "comment": "spllg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Culture_of_Plymouth"}
